and did a sort of rolling year,

50
00:02:40,471 --> 00:02:41,552
learning as much as I could

51
00:02:41,612 --> 00:02:43,533
from working for a variety of other studios.

52
00:02:44,534 --> 00:02:46,736
And one of the things I learned,

53
00:02:47,656 --> 00:02:49,257
although I worked with some really great people

54
00:02:49,538 --> 00:02:52,300
and I'd do it again, is that I'm not suited for AAA.

55
00:02:53,100 --> 00:02:55,342
So I founded Weather Factory with Lottie,

56
00:02:55,922 --> 00:02:56,923
with a brief, as I said,

57
00:02:56,943 --> 00:02:58,784
of making experimental narrative games.

58
00:02:59,905 --> 00:03:02,427
And Cultist Simulator, our debut game,

59
00:03:04,322 --> 00:03:09,244
We made it in 11 months, the budget was less than 200k USD.

60
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:14,105
It's done very good business and it's been nominated for two BAFTAs.

61
00:03:14,345 --> 00:03:19,507
So I'm speaking to you in the brief bright moment after we were nominated for the BAFTAs

62
00:03:19,687 --> 00:03:25,228
before we inevitably lose them to Florence and Obra Dinn but you know.

63
00:03:25,248 --> 00:03:25,288
So

64
00:03:30,577 --> 00:03:33,679
Let me talk about what it means to make experimental games

65
00:03:34,099 --> 00:03:35,380
that are also commercial games.

66
00:03:36,561 --> 00:03:39,683
Fallen London was my first project.

67
00:03:42,685 --> 00:03:45,266
And the idea behind Fallen London is unbelievably stupid.

68
00:03:45,307 --> 00:03:47,828
It is a content-heavy free-to-play browser game.

69
00:03:47,848 --> 00:03:49,609
The whole point about free-to-play games is

70
00:03:50,190 --> 00:03:51,811
you want people to shell out repeatedly

71
00:03:52,912 --> 00:03:54,232
for reproducible things,

72
00:03:54,693 --> 00:03:56,794
so you skin the same hat in 90 different ways

73
00:03:56,834 --> 00:03:58,275
and sell all the different gifts.

74
00:03:59,390 --> 00:04:01,250
Fallen in London, there was a talk on this,

75
00:04:01,290 --> 00:04:02,191
I think it's over this week,

76
00:04:03,591 --> 00:04:05,492
has a tremendous appetite for content

77
00:04:06,232 --> 00:04:07,752
because content is what fuels

78
00:04:07,772 --> 00:04:08,973
a lot of the free-to-play purchases.

79
00:04:08,993 --> 00:04:12,354
That was a stupid idea, as was designing it for web

80
00:04:12,554 --> 00:04:15,374
rather than mobile devices because in 2009,

81
00:04:16,035 --> 00:04:17,655
I didn't know anything about anything

82
00:04:17,695 --> 00:04:19,916
and I didn't realize that mobile was going to be a thing.

83
00:04:21,216 --> 00:04:22,236
It doesn't have a genre.

84
00:04:23,157 --> 00:04:25,397
It's very hard to elevate a pitch for in London

85
00:04:25,417 --> 00:04:26,558
or describe it in a sentence.

86
00:04:28,806 --> 00:04:30,467
Super grindy, sorry about that.

87
00:04:31,568 --> 00:04:32,409
And very divisive.

88
00:04:32,769 --> 00:04:34,090
People do tend to love it or hate it.

89
00:04:36,993 --> 00:04:38,974
This wasn't a design intention,

90
00:04:38,994 --> 00:04:42,477
but for a long time it looked like something

91
00:04:42,497 --> 00:04:45,120
that had been built by one and a half people

92
00:04:45,220 --> 00:04:47,242
in a back bedroom on zero budget.

93
00:04:48,022 --> 00:04:50,304
Nevertheless, when I left Valvetta,

94
00:04:51,425 --> 00:04:54,308
it was making enough money to pay a team consistently.

95
00:04:54,922 --> 00:04:56,863
Those aren't the kind of numbers that get Zynga excited,

96
00:04:57,063 --> 00:04:59,524
but for a zero budget passion project,

97
00:04:59,544 --> 00:05:01,125
it's seven years after launch, that's pretty good.

98
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:06,527
So the C, as any of you who've played it,

99
00:05:07,048 --> 00:05:08,308
or watched a Let's Play will know,

100
00:05:09,209 --> 00:05:11,690
is the world's slowest RPG.

101
00:05:11,710 --> 00:05:14,511
Which isn't really a traditional box point.

102
00:05:17,112 --> 00:05:18,073
It's also got permadeath.

103
00:05:18,893 --> 00:05:21,114
It's not sensible to put permadeath in an RPG,

104
00:05:21,894 --> 00:05:22,635
but we did.

105
00:05:26,376 --> 00:05:29,157
It's once again got no discernible genre.

106
00:05:29,177 --> 00:05:30,478
It's sort of an RPG,

107
00:05:31,238 --> 00:05:33,219
but I'm stretching the definition to say that honestly.

108
00:05:35,080 --> 00:05:36,881
And once again, it's very divisive

109
00:05:38,402 --> 00:05:39,922
and it did good numbers.

110
00:05:40,322 --> 00:05:42,183
Again, not good numbers if you're notch,

111
00:05:42,423 --> 00:05:44,744
but very good numbers if you're six people

112
00:05:45,285 --> 00:05:46,425
in a small room in South London.

113
00:05:48,946 --> 00:05:49,687
Cultist Simulator.

114
00:05:49,707 --> 00:05:50,907
So the first two, just for clarity,

115
00:05:50,927 --> 00:05:52,628
were Fail Better Games, my last studio.

116
00:05:53,388 --> 00:05:55,770
Cultist Simulator is Weather Factory's debut title.

117
00:05:56,905 --> 00:06:00,167
And once again, it's very hard to describe in a sentence,

118
00:06:01,227 --> 00:06:02,728
but it's deliberately obscure.

119
00:06:02,788 --> 00:06:04,970
It's more like sort of occult solitaire than anything else.

120
00:06:05,710 --> 00:06:07,491
And not only is it deliberately obscure,

121
00:06:07,591 --> 00:06:08,932
it has no tutorial,

122
00:06:09,893 --> 00:06:15,596
which is a choice we made with some nervousness.

123
00:06:16,337 --> 00:06:18,278
Make a deliberately obscure game with no tutorial.

124
00:06:19,559 --> 00:06:20,839
Doesn't have any kind of genre,

125
00:06:20,859 --> 00:06:22,721
C for divisive.

126
00:06:23,880 --> 00:06:25,541
And these are the numbers we're talking about.

127
00:06:25,761 --> 00:06:27,662
Very small budget, very good sales,

128
00:06:27,702 --> 00:06:29,964
considering especially what a tough market is out there.

129
00:06:31,225 --> 00:06:32,105
And we have denominations.

130
00:06:32,766 --> 00:06:34,947
So, what it means to be experimental.

131
00:06:35,687 --> 00:06:37,849
I'm gonna read this comment because I enjoy it.

132
00:06:39,010 --> 00:06:41,051
The approach is great, the ideas are great,

133
00:06:41,291 --> 00:06:42,432
and the setting and world building

134
00:06:42,452 --> 00:06:43,653
are interesting and refreshing.

135
00:06:43,913 --> 00:06:45,454
Why thank you, Reddit commenter.

136
00:06:45,874 --> 00:06:47,055
Reddit has a bad rep.

137
00:06:47,875 --> 00:06:49,136
But as a game design student,

138
00:06:49,941 --> 00:06:52,183
If I would have handed this in at any point during the year,

139
00:06:52,763 --> 00:06:54,084
they would have failed me instantly.

140
00:06:58,447 --> 00:07:00,629
This is key when you're talking about experimental stuff.

141
00:07:01,470 --> 00:07:03,631
Doing things that no one else is doing,

142
00:07:04,252 --> 00:07:05,633
things that people wouldn't normally do,

143
00:07:06,373 --> 00:07:09,055
is an advantage, all else being equal.

144
00:07:09,956 --> 00:07:11,037
It means creative innovation,

145
00:07:11,057 --> 00:07:12,778
it means commercial innovation,

146
00:07:13,258 --> 00:07:17,001
which in a market as tough as the one out there right now,

147
00:07:17,842 --> 00:07:18,362
is a big deal.

148
00:07:19,966 --> 00:07:21,226
But, there's a catch.

149
00:07:24,108 --> 00:07:25,668
Very often those things look stupid.

150
00:07:26,068 --> 00:07:28,729
Worse, often there are good reasons

151
00:07:28,769 --> 00:07:30,010
you put a tutorial in the game.

152
00:07:30,090 --> 00:07:31,030
Often there are good reasons

153
00:07:31,070 --> 00:07:32,271
why you were taught in your first year

154
00:07:32,331 --> 00:07:33,611
of game design the things you should do.

155
00:07:35,752 --> 00:07:36,592
And this is the catch.

156
00:07:37,193 --> 00:07:38,513
Until you actually do the thing,

157
00:07:38,533 --> 00:07:40,794
it's very hard to work out what's stupid

158
00:07:41,174 --> 00:07:42,135
and what just looks stupid.

159
00:07:43,604 --> 00:07:47,226
So to try to narrow down the things that have worked

160
00:07:47,306 --> 00:07:50,249
in the more experimental stuff that I've done over the years

161
00:07:50,969 --> 00:07:51,850
and the stuff that doesn't,

162
00:07:51,990 --> 00:07:54,052
I want to introduce you to my failures.

163
00:07:54,812 --> 00:07:56,053
These are not all my failures.

164
00:07:56,073 --> 00:07:58,015
These are only some of my failures.

165
00:07:58,815 --> 00:08:00,697
You won't even have heard of most of these,

166
00:08:00,877 --> 00:08:01,697
very good reasons.

167
00:08:02,298 --> 00:08:03,859
I wasn't creative lead on all of these,

168
00:08:06,161 --> 00:08:08,082
but I signed off on every one of them

169
00:08:08,443 --> 00:08:11,065
and I bear responsibility for their failure.

170
00:08:12,070 --> 00:08:19,533
Black Crown Project was back when I thought that free-to-play narrative was going to be the wave of the future and replace novels because I was insane.

171
00:08:20,053 --> 00:08:28,736
Story Nexus is the shared narrative platform which is going to make us a lot of money and instead nearly tanked Failbetter at the time.

172
00:08:30,497 --> 00:08:34,718
So I think probably I've had twice as many failures in my career as successors.

173
00:08:38,772 --> 00:08:42,035
Here are the things that I think the successors had

174
00:08:42,235 --> 00:08:43,136
that made them successors.

175
00:08:43,296 --> 00:08:46,198
One is that they were both distinctive and divisive.

176
00:08:47,359 --> 00:08:49,100
I'm gonna talk about the difference between that and a bit,

177
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:50,341
but both those things are important.

178
00:08:51,642 --> 00:08:52,763
They were all reasonably good.

179
00:08:54,064 --> 00:08:55,785
Sounds a bit like I'm being flipped when I say that.

180
00:08:56,466 --> 00:08:59,928
And people differ on the quality of some of them,

181
00:09:00,629 --> 00:09:02,390
but none of them were actively dreadful.

182
00:09:04,637 --> 00:09:08,199
All of them very important, super small budgets

183
00:09:08,499 --> 00:09:12,640
by the standards of game dev and very short timelines.

184
00:09:12,680 --> 00:09:15,582
Cultist Simulator, 11 months, Sunless Sea, 16 months.

185
00:09:16,122 --> 00:09:19,723
Fallen London, from the time we wrote the first line of code

186
00:09:19,743 --> 00:09:22,705
to the time we launched in public beta,

187
00:09:22,845 --> 00:09:24,305
was I think four months,

188
00:09:24,625 --> 00:09:26,066
although it's been worked on ever since.

189
00:09:27,223 --> 00:09:29,224
And a suite of design techniques

190
00:09:29,544 --> 00:09:31,565
to which I'm going to give the super fancy name

191
00:09:31,985 --> 00:09:33,106
of Apothenian design.

192
00:09:33,126 --> 00:09:34,726
And I'll come back and talk about that in a minute.

193
00:09:36,687 --> 00:09:38,447
So why all these things?

194
00:09:38,768 --> 00:09:39,508
Why are they useful?

195
00:09:39,528 --> 00:09:40,368
Why are they important?

196
00:09:41,429 --> 00:09:43,229
Particularly if you're an indie dev,

197
00:09:43,969 --> 00:09:47,131
it's vital to lean into your limitations.

198
00:09:48,291 --> 00:09:49,711
All studios have limitations.

199
00:09:51,152 --> 00:09:53,393
Indie studios are basically made of limitations.

200
00:09:55,489 --> 00:09:57,711
I used this slide in my talk last year, but I love it,

201
00:09:57,731 --> 00:09:58,552
so you're getting it again.

202
00:09:59,913 --> 00:10:03,095
This is one of the characters, one of the primary characters

203
00:10:03,115 --> 00:10:06,378
from the popular science documentary, Aliens.

204
00:10:09,260 --> 00:10:12,403
It's the M577 armored personnel carrier,

205
00:10:13,744 --> 00:10:16,506
and it's made of all kinds of fantastic science ship,

206
00:10:17,267 --> 00:10:19,909
and it's basically indestructible, and it's very expensive.

207
00:10:20,750 --> 00:10:22,351
You probably remember that it doesn't make it

208
00:10:22,391 --> 00:10:23,312
all the way through the film.

209
00:10:26,553 --> 00:10:27,414
This is Rebecca Jordan.

210
00:10:28,916 --> 00:10:29,737
She's nine years old,

211
00:10:30,158 --> 00:10:31,940
she has a second grade citizenship award,

212
00:10:32,601 --> 00:10:35,365
and she has one very important limitation.

213
00:10:36,046 --> 00:10:37,288
She's really small.

214
00:10:38,650 --> 00:10:40,452
So her lifespan is much greater than that of the M577.

215
00:10:42,938 --> 00:10:46,400
And as an indie studio, you're not the APC, you're new.

216
00:10:47,161 --> 00:10:50,223
So find what your limitations are and lean into them.

217
00:10:50,623 --> 00:10:52,704
Some of those limitations are common to everybody

218
00:10:52,724 --> 00:10:54,165
who's reasonably described as indie.

219
00:10:54,605 --> 00:10:56,366
Small budgets, limited resources.

220
00:10:57,267 --> 00:10:59,668
There were two talks on the wind physics

221
00:10:59,908 --> 00:11:02,710
of God of War, this GDC,

222
00:11:02,830 --> 00:11:04,411
and I'm sure both of them were excellent

223
00:11:05,311 --> 00:11:06,452
for specialized audiences,

224
00:11:06,492 --> 00:11:08,013
but I've never made a game with wind physics.

225
00:11:09,153 --> 00:11:10,674
So all our limitations are different,

226
00:11:10,694 --> 00:11:12,295
but they tend to overlap in similar places.

227
00:11:13,428 --> 00:11:14,489
and that's what this talk is about.

228
00:11:16,569 --> 00:11:19,670
So being distinctive, and the problem with this slide

229
00:11:19,930 --> 00:11:22,230
is that giving you advice on how to be distinctive

230
00:11:22,450 --> 00:11:27,131
is of limited use because if I tell you all

231
00:11:27,171 --> 00:11:28,371
what to do to be distinctive,

232
00:11:29,391 --> 00:11:30,972
assuming it's good advice to do it,

233
00:11:32,012 --> 00:11:33,452
assuming you go out and do that,

234
00:11:33,852 --> 00:11:35,853
congratulations, none of you are distinctive.

235
00:11:36,653 --> 00:11:38,333
So find what makes you distinctive,

236
00:11:38,413 --> 00:11:40,453
find your specific limitations and lean into them.

237
00:11:41,447 --> 00:11:45,129
But because they've given me a free pass for GDC and everything,

238
00:11:45,189 --> 00:11:48,531
I have to give some specific advice rather than talking happy generalities.

239
00:11:48,832 --> 00:11:51,093
So let me give you a couple of pieces of advice.

240
00:11:52,454 --> 00:11:52,794
One is this.

241
00:11:54,441 --> 00:11:56,382
So this is the key art for Cultist

242
00:11:56,582 --> 00:11:59,784
that the insanely talented Catherine Unger did for us.

243
00:12:01,185 --> 00:12:04,026
It doesn't tell you anything about the experience

244
00:12:04,426 --> 00:12:05,587
of playing the game.

245
00:12:05,627 --> 00:12:06,347
Sorry, let me rephrase that.

246
00:12:06,367 --> 00:12:07,288
It doesn't tell you anything about

247
00:12:07,328 --> 00:12:08,709
what you actually do in the game.

248
00:12:09,329 --> 00:12:11,190
It does tell you something about the experience

249
00:12:11,230 --> 00:12:11,950
of playing the game.

250
00:12:11,970 --> 00:12:14,332
It evokes some of the emotions

251
00:12:16,053 --> 00:12:17,774
and some of the setting details you're gonna deal with.

252
00:12:17,814 --> 00:12:19,575
And once you've seen it, you tend to remember it.

253
00:12:23,182 --> 00:12:25,244
Very, very annoying thing.

254
00:12:25,284 --> 00:12:27,185
If you're a writer, as I primarily am,

255
00:12:27,825 --> 00:12:30,848
art is much more distinctive than text.

256
00:12:30,888 --> 00:12:33,489
A wall of text looks like a wall of text from a distance,

257
00:12:34,410 --> 00:12:37,212
but art immediately looks distinctive.

