1212
00:57:42,515 --> 00:57:44,296
I have a question about failures.

1213
00:57:45,917 --> 00:57:49,180
Specifically, do you have any advice

1214
00:57:49,280 --> 00:57:53,744
for drawing the line between calling something dead

1215
00:57:53,764 --> 00:57:57,767
or starting over and trying something new

1216
00:57:57,907 --> 00:58:00,770
to work with the same idea?

1217
00:58:02,968 --> 00:58:06,411
So the question is where do you draw the line around failures when you call something dead?

1218
00:58:06,511 --> 00:58:10,195
My answer, this may not be the question you're asking, but it's always ship it.

1219
00:58:10,576 --> 00:58:14,600
If you think it's going to fail, finish it up and ship it anyway, because even if it

1220
00:58:14,640 --> 00:58:18,043
sells exactly zero copies, you will learn something from the process of finishing it

1221
00:58:18,544 --> 00:58:20,766
and you will eschew regret.

1222
00:58:21,941 --> 00:58:24,263
I think, I mean I said all those things are failures,

1223
00:58:24,303 --> 00:58:25,403
some are more failures than others,

1224
00:58:25,464 --> 00:58:27,345
I think a little bit melodramatic.

1225
00:58:27,545 --> 00:58:30,787
Below, for example, never made its Kickstarter target.

1226
00:58:31,368 --> 00:58:34,230
Silvertree did make its Kickstarter target.

1227
00:58:34,290 --> 00:58:35,471
It raised money for the company,

1228
00:58:35,491 --> 00:58:36,732
it kept people employed a bit longer,

1229
00:58:36,772 --> 00:58:38,493
but it was not well received

1230
00:58:38,573 --> 00:58:40,294
because we didn't do a great job of it.

1231
00:58:41,255 --> 00:58:45,938
I think, yeah, let your audience decide if it's a failure

1232
00:58:45,958 --> 00:58:47,940
I think is the best answer I can give.

1233
00:58:47,960 --> 00:58:48,920
